President Joe Biden and Prime Minister Justin Trudeau of Canada met in Mexico City to discuss various topics, including economic competitiveness, climate commitments, security and defense cooperation, and regional and global challenges. They talked about strengthening supply chains for critical minerals, electric vehicles, and semiconductors, as well as combating climate change and transforming North America into a clean energy powerhouse. The leaders also discussed defense and security cooperation, with a focus on supporting Ukraine against Russia's aggression and ensuring the defense and security of North America. They addressed the security and humanitarian situation in Haiti and emphasized the importance of collaboration on migration issues, including expanding legal pathways and increasing refugee resettlement. Additionally, they reaffirmed their commitment to promoting human rights and defending democratic values, including supporting democratic institutions in Brazil. President Biden expressed his anticipation for a visit to Canada in March of this year.